  {
    "user": "U02U0AS3J49",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1731790489.920349",
    "client_msg_id": "de623433-ae4f-4f85-8430-ad23e7c0b823",
    "text": "Taking a look, but I'm not far in, and I'm unfamiliar with the terrain. I have found that some of the most effective uses of my own tool have been as an executable medium of communication, to help different people know whether they were communicating complicated things successfully, because when they had, everyone agreed that the code was behaving in accordance with their understanding. I wonder if that \"code as a medium of clarifying conversation\" idea is a cousin of \"code as a medium of performance\", and if they have as a shared grandparent \"code as a medium of human communication\", which has as other grandchildren things like \"code as communication between developers,\" which speaks to things developers are more familiar with, like comments, and naming conventions... Does it all grow out of \"code is about people\"?",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1731755266.342289",
    "parent_user_id": "U03R0B9U1GD",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "p32Av",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Taking a look, but I'm not far in, and I'm unfamiliar with the terrain. I have found that some of the most effective uses of my own tool have been as an executable medium of communication, to help different people know whether they were communicating complicated things successfully, because when they had, everyone agreed that the code was behaving in accordance with their understanding. I wonder if that \"code as a medium of clarifying conversation\" idea is a cousin of \"code as a medium of performance\", and if they have as a shared grandparent \"code as a medium of human communication\", which has as other grandchildren things like \"code as communication between developers,\" which speaks to things developers are more familiar with, like comments, and naming conventions... Does it all grow out of \"code is about people\"?"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "channel_name": "linking-together",
    "channel_id": "C5U3SEW6A"
  },
  {
    "user": "U07CGRNH6S2",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1731798320.158489",
    "client_msg_id": "bd87b69f-19f6-42be-a732-98366bf3bac6",
    "text": "It is worth _thinking_ and gaining perspectives. Some thoughts are then worthy - or not, it depends. For instance for me, it is clear that data-first has certain limits, and eg. model-first thinking is more powerful approach.  If a cell in a spreadsheet has a lot of data, there is basically no practical way of inspecting it. If it has a lot of functions, there is a little chance to make sense out of it, which is at least possible with programming langs",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1731714636.906459",
    "parent_user_id": "U07TREJC9DJ",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "Ok7as",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "It is worth "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "thinking",
                "style": {
                  "italic": true
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " and gaining perspectives. Some thoughts are then worthy - or not, it depends. For instance for me, it is clear that data-first has certain limits, and eg. model-first thinking is more powerful approach.  If a cell in a spreadsheet has a lot of data, there is basically no practical way of inspecting it. If it has a lot of functions, there is a little chance to make sense out of it, which is at least possible with programming langs"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
